.SH DESCRIPTION
\fBviewperf\fP is a benchmark for measuring OpenGL performance and was 
developed primarily by IBM with contributions from other members of the
OpenGL Performance Characterization (OPC) Committee.  A unique aspect
of \fBviewperf\fP is its overall generality.  It supports two fundamental
geometry data formats:  ASCII and binary.  The ASCII geometry data sets
are commercially available from Viewpoit DataLabs, Orem, Utah (1-800-DATASET),
from which the benchmark name was derived.  An ASCII data set can be
rendered as points, disjoint lines (vectors), lines, polygons, triangles, 
quads, or triangle fans.  The binary data set provieds an alternative to 
the ASCII format in providing faster parse times for large objects and 
supporting line strips and triangle strips in addition to points and 
disjoint lines (vectors).  In addition to \fBviewperf\fP's rendering modes
which specify the fundamental primitive type such as point, line, polygon
or triangle strip, serveral command line options are also provided to
specify how the object will be rendered.  These options include:
.HP 
\- buffer controls (framebuffer, depth buffer, alpha buffer, etc.)
.HP
\- granularity of color attributes (per frame, per primitive, per vertex)
.HP
\- shading model (flat or smooth)
.HP
\- lighting model (local/infinite lights, local/infinite viewer, two-sided lighting)
.HP
\- texture mapping
.HP
\- line and polygon stippling (patterns)
.HP
\- line and polygon anti-aliasing
.HP
\- fogging (depth-cueing)
.HP
\- clipping
.HP
\- immediate or display list modes
.HP
\- direct/indirect rendering
.P
Defining a \fBviewperf\fP run requires a geometry data set and rendering
mode in addition to all the rendering options desired.
The performance data provided by \fBviewperf\fP is reported as a frame
rate (frames/second).  Therefore, larger numbers indicate better performance.
